Kitadate Daigakusuke Toshinaga became the lord of [[Tateyama Castle]] in [[Keichō]] 6 (1601) and planned the irrigation of the eastern part of the [[Shonai Plain]]. He completed the irrigation canal in Keichō 17 (1616), known as the "Kitadate Great Weir," which remains a crucial waterway for the eastern Shonai Plain. In [[Kan'ei]] 2 (1625), 153 years after his death, the local residents benefiting from the waterway erected a shrine dedicated to Toshinaga in the precincts of Kariyawa Hachimangu and called it "Kitadate Suijin Shrine." In [[Taishō]] 8 (1919), the shrine was moved to the site of Tateyama Castle and became an independent shrine named "Kitadate Shrine." It was designated a [[Gōsha]] in Taishō 11 (1922) and became a [[Separate Table Shrine]] of the [[Association of Shinto Shrines]] in [[Shōwa]] 36 (1961). In Shōwa 48 (1973), a new shrine building was constructed at the current site in Kasayama.

The [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] destroyer ''[[Mogami-class destroyer|Mogami]]'' commissioned in Shōwa 36 enshrined a spirit of Kitadate Shrine as its guardian deity.

